'''Dima Khatib''' ({{lang-ar|Ø¯ÙÙ Ø© Ø§ÙØ®Ø·ÙØ¨}}) is a [[Syria]]n-born [[Palestine|Palestinian]] <ref>http://www.dimakhatib.com/</ref> journalist. Since 1997, she has worked as a correspondent, producer, and Latin America Bureau Chief for the [[Al Jazeera]] network.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sandraoffthestrip.com/tag/dima-khatib/ |title=Dima Khatib &#124; Off the Strip for free thinkers and adventurers |publisher=Sandraoffthestrip.com |date=2011-02-18 |accessdate=2011-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title= Global Media Go to War: Role of News and Entertainment Media During the 2003 Iraq War|editor=Ralph D. Berenger |year=2004 |publisher=Marquette Books |location= |isbn=9780922993109 |page=66 |pages= |url=http://books.google.com.tr/books?id=d6LtAAAAMAAJ&q=%22dima+khatib%22&dq=%22dima+khatib%22&hl=tr&ei=s_SITczrOsXOswbl0bi-DA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAA}}</ref>. Khatib speaks eight languages ([[Arabic]], [[English language|English]], [[French language|French]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], [[Italian language|Italian]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[German language|German]]).
Prior to her work with Al Jazeera, Khatib has worked for Swiss Radio International in [[Bern]]. During the [[Iraq War]], she worked as a live news producer in [[Doha]]. She gave an interview to CNN's [[Larry King]] and [[Wolf Blitzer]],<ref>{{cite news| url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0304/09/lkl.00.html | work=CNN | title=CNN.com}}</ref> and was featured in ''[[Control Room (film)|Control Room]]'', a 2004 documentary film about Al Jazeera and its coverage of the 2003 invasion of Iraq.<ref>{{cite news| url = http://news.independent.co.uk/media/story.jsp?story=603895 | archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20050306020202/http://news.independent.co.uk/media/story.jsp?story=603895| archivedate = 2005-03-06| title = Broadcast and be damned| author = Shiv Malik| publisher = The Independent| date = 2005-01-24| accessdate = 2010-12-07| location=London}}</ref>
During her assignment as the Latin America Bureau Chief, she reported that ChÃ¡vez was the first head of state to harshly condemn Israel over the Israeli-Lebanon conflict.<ref name=Khatib>http://english.aljazeera.net/NR/exeres/0393C044-9D53-43FB-9B2F-3F15DF88AF91.htm</ref> She dismissed the claims that Gaddafi has escaped to Venezuela reporting from Caracas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://axisoflogic.com/artman/publish/Article_62339.shtml |title=Libya protests spread and intensify &#124; World News |publisher=Axisoflogic.com |date=2011-02-22 |accessdate=2011-04-12}}</ref> She received attention during Arab revolutions for providing frequent updates and commentary about recent events via her [[Twitter]] account.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://thelede.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/01/14/arab-bloggers-cheer-on-tunisias-revolution/ | work=The New York Times | first=Robert | last=Mackey | title=Arab Bloggers Cheer on Tunisia's Revolution | date=2011-01-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/blog/2011/jan/17/tunisia-live-updates | location=London | work=The Guardian | first1=Paul | last1=Owen | first2=Matthew | last2=Weaver | title=Tunisia crisis: live updates | date=2011-01-17}}</ref>
